const BIOLOGY_DATA = [

// ======================== CH1: TRANSPORTATION IN PLANTS ========================
// STUDY NOTES — Transport of Food and Minerals in Plants
{id:"b1sn1",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Study Notes — Overview",
 content:'Transport of Food and Minerals in Plants (Class 8 Biology)\n\nPlants need a specialized transport system to move water, minerals, and food to various parts of their structure. This system is primarily driven by two types of vascular tissues: Xylem and Phloem.',
 explanation:'Without transport, roots could absorb water but leaves would starve; leaves could make food but roots could not use it. Xylem and phloem work together as the plant\'s circulatory network.',
 teacherTip:'Chapter title says "food AND minerals" — xylem for minerals/water, phloem for food.',examTip:'Name both xylem and phloem when introducing plant transport.'},
{id:"b1sn2",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Study Notes — 1. Plant Vascular System",
 content:'The vascular system consists of tube-like tissues that act as pipelines throughout the plant.\n\nXYLEM (Water & Mineral Transport)\n• Function: Conducts water and dissolved minerals from the roots up to the leaves and aerial parts.\n• Direction: Unidirectional (moves only upwards).\n• Structure: Mostly dead cells without protoplasm. Tracheids and xylem vessels are placed end-to-end forming a continuous, straw-like passage. Lignified walls make them stiff, provide structural support, and prevent collapsing.\n• Components: Xylem vessels, tracheids, xylem fibres, and xylem parenchyma.\n• Location: Inner side of the vascular bundle.\n\nPHLOEM (Food Transport)\n• Function: Transports manufactured food (sugar molecules) from the leaves to all other parts.\n• Direction: Bidirectional (moves both upwards and downwards).\n• Structure: Mostly living cells. Sieve tubes are stacked to form long channels.\n• Components: Sieve tubes, companion cells, phloem parenchyma (stores food), and phloem fibres.\n• Location: Outer side of the vascular bundle.',
 explanation:'Xylem is like a one-way water pipe (dead, strong walls). Phloem is like a two-way food highway (living sieve tubes).',
 teacherTip:'Remember: Xylem = inner bundle, dead, up only. Phloem = outer bundle, living, up and down.',examTip:'Compare function, direction, cell type, and location of xylem vs phloem.'},
{id:"b1sn3",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Study Notes — 2. Absorption by the Roots",
 content:'Roots absorb water and essential minerals from the soil through specialized root hairs.\n\n• Root Hairs: Unicellular, thin-walled outgrowths of the root epidermis. They greatly increase surface area for maximum absorption.\n• Cell Sap: Fluid in the vacuole containing water and dissolved mineral salts.\n\nHow Plants Absorb Water and Minerals:\n1. OSMOSIS (Water) — Movement through a semi-permeable membrane from higher water concentration (soil) to lower (root). Does NOT require energy.\n2. DIFFUSION (Minerals/Salts) — Movement from higher to lower concentration. Does NOT require energy.\n3. ACTIVE TRANSPORT (Mineral Ions) — Movement from lower concentration (soil) to higher (root cells). REQUIRES energy (ATP).\n\nExample: A shriveled brinjal placed in water looks fresh again — water enters cells via osmosis because water concentration is higher outside the vegetable.',
 explanation:'Water sneaks in by osmosis; some minerals drift in by diffusion; scarce minerals are pumped in actively using cell energy.',
 teacherTip:'Osmosis = water only. Active transport = minerals against the gradient — needs ATP.',examTip:'State whether each process needs energy when comparing osmosis, diffusion, and active transport.'},
{id:"b1sn4",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Study Notes — 3. Ascent of Sap",
 content:'The upward movement of sap (water and minerals) through the xylem is called the ASCENT OF SAP. It is driven by two main forces:\n\n1. ROOT PRESSURE: Continuous inflow of water into the roots builds up pressure, physically pushing sap upwards into the stem.\n\n2. TRANSPIRATION PULL: As water evaporates from the leaves, it creates a powerful suction force (like drinking through a straw) that pulls water up from the roots.',
 explanation:'Root pressure gives a gentle push from below; transpiration pull provides the main suction from above — especially in tall plants.',
 teacherTip:'Transpiration pull is the dominant force in most plants; root pressure helps especially at night.',examTip:'Name both root pressure and transpiration pull for ascent of sap.'},
{id:"b1sn5",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Study Notes — 4. Transpiration & Translocation",
 content:'TRANSPIRATION\n• Definition: Loss of water as water vapour through stomata (tiny pores on the underside of leaves) and other aerial parts.\n• Importance:\n  — Cooling Effect: Evaporation cools the plant surface.\n  — Ascent of Sap: Creates low water potential in leaves, pulling water and minerals up from roots.\n• WILTING: If transpiration exceeds root absorption, cells lose turgor pressure and leaves, stems, and flowers droop.\n\nTRANSLOCATION\n• Definition: Transport of soluble products of photosynthesis (sugars) from leaves to the rest of the plant.\n• Mechanism: Occurs strictly through phloem tissues.',
 explanation:'Transpiration = water OUT through leaves (cooling + pull). Translocation = food OUT from leaves to everywhere else via phloem.',
 teacherTip:'Wilting = losing water faster than roots can replace it.',examTip:'Do not confuse transpiration (water loss) with translocation (food transport).'},
{id:"b1sn6",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Study Notes — 5. Plant Nutrients",
 content:'Plants require specific nutrients from the soil to grow properly:\n\n• MACRO-NUTRIENTS: Required in large quantities (e.g., Nitrogen).\n• MICRO-NUTRIENTS: Required in very small trace amounts (e.g., Boron, Manganese, Zinc).\n\nNote: Mineral deficiencies cause plant diseases. For example, lack of Zinc causes CHLOROSIS (yellowing of leaves).',
 explanation:'Macro = big amounts (N, P, K). Micro = tiny traces but still essential — missing them causes visible disease symptoms.',
 teacherTip:'Chlorosis = yellow leaves often linked to mineral deficiency, not just lack of water.',examTip:'Give one macro-nutrient and one micro-nutrient example; link Zinc deficiency to chlorosis.'},
// TEXTBOOK (bio1 OCR) — additional notes, no overlap with Study Notes above
{id:"b1ocr-n1",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Textbook — Diffusion & Unicellular Transport",
 content:'DIFFUSION: The net movement of molecules (gas, liquid or solid) from a region of higher concentration to a region of lower concentration until they spread evenly.\n\nIn unicellular organisms (Chlamydomonas) and simple multicellular plants (Spirogyra), diffusion is the major method of transport. In tall higher plants, diffusion is too slow — special vascular channels (xylem and phloem) are needed.',
 explanation:'Simple plants are small enough for diffusion alone; complex plants need pipes (vascular tissues) for fast long-distance transport.',
 teacherTip:'Chlamydomonas = unicellular algae; Spirogyra = simple filamentous alga — both use diffusion.',examTip:'Name Chlamydomonas or Spirogyra when asked about diffusion-based transport.'},
{id:"b1ocr-n2",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Textbook — Girdling Experiment",
 content:'GIRDLING EXPERIMENT: A ring of bark (phloem) is removed from the stem, blocking downward food transport.\n\nObservation: The region ABOVE the girdled area swells due to accumulation of food; the portion BELOW does not swell.\n\nConclusion: Food synthesised in leaves is transported downward through phloem in the bark.',
 explanation:'Swelling above the cut proves food moves down through phloem; without bark, food cannot pass the girdle.',
 teacherTip:'Girdling = remove bark only, not the wood (xylem).',examTip:'Girdling demonstrates phloem transport of food, NOT food synthesis.'},
{id:"b1ocr-n3",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Textbook — Factors Affecting Transpiration",
 content:'Factors affecting the rate of transpiration:\n\n• WIND: Transpiration increases with wind velocity (removes humid air around leaves).\n• HUMIDITY: High humidity around the leaf reduces transpiration.\n• AVAILABILITY OF SOIL WATER: Dry soil reduces water uptake, lowering transpiration rate.\n• TEMPERATURE & LIGHT: Higher temperature and light generally increase transpiration.',
 explanation:'Hot, dry, windy days = maximum water loss. Humid, calm, cool days = slower transpiration.',
 teacherTip:'Wilting happens when transpiration outpaces root water uptake.',examTip:'List at least three factors: wind, humidity, soil water, temperature.'},
{id:"b1ocr-n4",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Textbook — Mineral Deficiency Diseases",
 content:'Deficiency diseases due to lack of essential nutrients:\n\n1. NITROGEN (macronutrient): Poor growth; old leaves turn yellow (chlorosis).\n2. POTASSIUM (macronutrient): Leaf tips turn yellow; affects enzyme activation and water balance.\n3. MAGNESIUM (macronutrient): Chlorosis — yellowing of leaves (Mg is part of chlorophyll).\n4. COPPER (micronutrient): Bluish hue in leaves.\n5. MOLYBDENUM (micronutrient): Stunting; leaves fail to develop dark green colour.\n6. ZINC (micronutrient): Pale leaves with dark spots on edges; affects enzyme and auxin synthesis.',
 explanation:'Each missing mineral shows a specific visible symptom — chlorosis is the most common exam answer.',
 teacherTip:'Link chlorosis to nitrogen OR magnesium deficiency depending on which leaves yellow first.',examTip:'Give mineral name + symptom + macro/micro classification for full marks.'},
{id:"b1ocr-n5",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Textbook — Xylem Structure",
 content:'XYLEM is a complex tissue with both living (parenchyma) and dead (sclerenchyma) cells. Four elements: tracheids, vessels, xylem fibres, and xylem parenchyma.\n\n• Tracheids & vessels: tube-like, lignified walls — conduct water.\n• Xylem fibres: thick-walled, provide mechanical support.\n• Xylem parenchyma: living cells for storage.\n\nIn mature plants, xylem is popularly known as WOOD.',
 explanation:'Lignin makes xylem walls stiff so water columns do not collapse under transpiration pull.',
 teacherTip:'Xylem parenchyma is LIVING — do not say all xylem cells are dead.',examTip:'Name all four xylem elements when describing structure.'},
{id:"b1ocr-n6",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Textbook — Passive vs Active Transport",
 content:'ACTIVE TRANSPORT: Movement of molecules across a semi-permeable membrane AGAINST a concentration gradient using energy (ATP). Root hairs absorb minerals this way when soil concentration is lower than cell sap.\n\nPASSIVE TRANSPORT: Water absorption controlled by transpiration pull — roots act as a passive absorbing surface; no energy needed for water entry by osmosis.',
 explanation:'Minerals often need active pumping; water follows osmosis and transpiration pull passively.',
 teacherTip:'Active = against gradient + needs ATP. Passive = with gradient, no energy.',examTip:'Compare active transport (minerals) with osmosis (water) in roots.'},
// NOTES
{id:"b1n1",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Why Plants Need Transport",content:'Plants need a transport system to carry water and minerals from roots to leaves, and food (sugars) from leaves to all other parts. Unlike animals, plants do not have a heart — they rely on special tissues called XYLEM and PHLOEM.',explanation:'Roots absorb water from soil, but photosynthesis happens in leaves. A transport system bridges this gap so every cell gets what it needs.',teacherTip:'Think of xylem as the "water pipe" and phloem as the "food delivery truck."',examTip:'Always name both xylem AND phloem when asked about plant transport tissues.'},
{id:"b1n2",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Xylem — Water Transport",content:'XYLEM carries water and dissolved minerals UPWARD from roots to leaves. It is made of dead, hollow cells forming continuous tubes. The movement is driven by TRANSPIRATION PULL — as water evaporates from leaves, it creates a suction that pulls water up.',explanation:'Imagine drinking through a straw — when you suck from the top, liquid rises from the bottom. Transpiration creates a similar pull in the plant.',teacherTip:'Xylem = dead cells, one-way (UP only). Remember "X-UP" — X for xylem, UP for direction.',examTip:'Mention "transpiration pull" as the driving force for water transport in xylem.'},
{id:"b1n3",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Phloem — Food Transport",content:'PHLOEM carries prepared food (mainly sucrose) from leaves to all parts of the plant. This process is called TRANSLOCATION. Phloem is made of living cells called sieve tubes with companion cells. Food moves both UP and DOWN.',explanation:'After photosynthesis makes sugar in leaves, phloem delivers it everywhere — to roots for storage, to fruits for sweetness, to growing tips for energy.',teacherTip:'Phloem = living cells, two-way (up AND down). Remember "Phloem = Food."',examTip:'Use the term "translocation" specifically for food transport in phloem.'},
{id:"b1n4",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Transpiration",content:'TRANSPIRATION is the loss of water vapour from the aerial parts of a plant, mainly through tiny pores called STOMATA on leaves. It helps in: (i) pulling water upward, (ii) cooling the plant, (iii) helping mineral absorption. Factors affecting transpiration: temperature, humidity, wind, light intensity.',explanation:'On a hot, dry, windy day, plants lose water faster. Each leaf has thousands of stomata that open and close to regulate water loss.',teacherTip:'Transpiration is like the plant "sweating" — it cools the plant and drives water flow.',examTip:'List at least 3 functions of transpiration for full marks.'},
{id:"b1n5",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Root Hair Absorption",content:'Root hairs are thin extensions of root cells that increase the surface area for absorbing water and minerals from soil. Water enters root hairs by OSMOSIS (movement of water from a region of higher water concentration to lower water concentration through a semi-permeable membrane).',explanation:'Root hairs are like tiny fingers reaching into the soil to grab as much water as possible. More surface area = more absorption.',teacherTip:'Root hair cell walls are thin and have no cuticle — perfectly designed for absorption.',examTip:'Define osmosis precisely — mention "semi-permeable membrane" for full marks.'},
// TRUE/FALSE
{id:"b1tf1",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Xylem carries food from leaves to other parts of the plant.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:"False. Xylem carries WATER and minerals upward. PHLOEM carries food (translocation).",teacherTip:'Xylem = Water, Phloem = Food. Never mix them up!',examTip:'This is one of the most commonly tested mix-ups in biology exams.'},
{id:"b1tf2",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Transpiration helps in the upward movement of water in plants.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:"True. Transpiration creates a suction force (transpiration pull) that draws water upward through the xylem.",teacherTip:'Transpiration pull is the main driving force for water movement in tall trees.',examTip:'Connect transpiration to "pull" or "suction" for scientific accuracy.'},
{id:"b1tf3",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Phloem is made up of dead cells.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:"False. Phloem is made of LIVING cells (sieve tubes and companion cells). Xylem is made of dead cells.",teacherTip:'Living = Phloem, Dead = Xylem.',examTip:'This distinction between xylem and phloem is a very common exam question.'},
{id:"b1tf4",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Water enters root hair cells by osmosis.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:"True. Soil water has higher water concentration than root hair cell sap, so water moves in by osmosis through the semi-permeable cell membrane.",teacherTip:'Osmosis is a special type of diffusion — only for water through a membrane.',examTip:'Always mention "semi-permeable membrane" when defining osmosis.'},
// FILL BLANKS
{id:"b1fb1",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The tissue that transports water in plants is called ______.",blankAnswer:"xylem",answer:"Xylem transports water and dissolved minerals from roots to leaves.",teacherTip:'X for Xylem, X marks the spot where water goes UP.',examTip:'Spell "xylem" correctly — common spelling mistake in exams.'},
{id:"b1fb2",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The transport of food in phloem is called ______.",blankAnswer:"translocation",answer:"Translocation is the movement of food materials (mainly sucrose) through phloem from leaves to other plant parts.",teacherTip:'"Trans" = across, "location" = places. Food moves across locations!',examTip:'Use "translocation" (not "transportation") specifically for phloem food movement.'},
{id:"b1fb3",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The tiny pores on leaf surface through which transpiration occurs are called ______.",blankAnswer:"stomata",answer:"Stomata (singular: stoma) are tiny pores on the leaf surface surrounded by guard cells that control their opening and closing.",teacherTip:'Guard cells are like bouncers at a club door — they decide when stomata open or close.',examTip:'Mention "guard cells" when discussing stomata for extra marks.'},
// MCQ
{id:"b1mcq1",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Which tissue carries water upward in plants?",options:["Phloem","Xylem","Parenchyma","Epidermis"],correctOption:1,answer:"Xylem carries water and dissolved minerals upward from roots to leaves. It consists of dead, hollow cells.",teacherTip:'Xylem = Water highway going UP.',examTip:'If the question mentions "upward" and "water," the answer is always xylem.'},
{id:"b1mcq2",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Transpiration mainly occurs through:",options:["Roots","Stem","Stomata on leaves","Flowers"],correctOption:2,answer:"Most transpiration (about 90%) occurs through stomata on leaves. A small amount occurs through the stem (lenticels).",teacherTip:'Leaves are the main transpiration organs because they have thousands of stomata.',examTip:'Specify "stomata on leaves" rather than just "leaves" for precision.'},
// SHORT ANSWER
{id:"b1sa1",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Differentiate between xylem and phloem.",answer:'XYLEM:\n• Transports water and minerals\n• Direction: upward only (roots → leaves)\n• Made of dead, hollow cells\n• Driven by transpiration pull\n\nPHLOEM:\n• Transports food (sugars)\n• Direction: both up and down\n• Made of living cells (sieve tubes)\n• Process called translocation',teacherTip:'Make a comparison table with at least 4 points for full marks.',examTip:'Always compare at least 4 features: what they carry, direction, cell type, and process name.'},
{id:"b1sa2",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"What is transpiration? State three of its functions.",answer:'TRANSPIRATION: The loss of water vapour from aerial parts of a plant, mainly through stomata on leaves.\n\nFunctions:\n1. Creates transpiration pull that helps in upward movement of water\n2. Cools the plant surface (evaporative cooling)\n3. Helps in absorption and transport of minerals from soil\n4. Maintains water balance in the plant',teacherTip:'Transpiration = plant sweating. It cools AND pulls water up.',examTip:'List at least 3 functions clearly numbered for full marks.'},
{id:"b1sa3",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Define osmosis. How does it help in water absorption by roots?",answer:'OSMOSIS: The movement of water molecules from a region of higher water concentration to a region of lower water concentration through a semi-permeable membrane.\n\nIn roots: Soil water (dilute solution) has higher water concentration than root hair cell sap (concentrated solution). So water moves from soil INTO root hair cells by osmosis through the semi-permeable cell membrane. This absorbed water then passes from cell to cell until it reaches the xylem.',teacherTip:'Osmosis always goes from dilute to concentrated — water follows the "thirsty" cells.',examTip:'The three key parts of osmosis definition: water molecules, concentration gradient, semi-permeable membrane.'},
// TEXTBOOK EXERCISES (bio1 OCR)
{id:"b1ocr-mcq1",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Textbook — I. Tick the Correct Choice",
 question:"Carrying of substances like food, water and minerals from one part to another is called:",
 options:["circulation","transpiration","excretion","transportation"],correctOption:3,
 answer:"Transportation is the carrying of food, water and minerals from one part of the plant body to another.",teacherTip:'Transportation ≠ transpiration (water loss only).',examTip:'General movement of substances = transportation.'},
{id:"b1ocr-mcq2",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Textbook — I. Tick the Correct Choice",
 question:"Diffusion is the method of transportation in:",
 options:["Chlamydomonas","human","insects","fish"],correctOption:0,
 answer:"In unicellular Chlamydomonas and simple plants like Spirogyra, materials move mainly by diffusion.",teacherTip:'Chlamydomonas = single-celled alga.',examTip:'Unicellular/simple plants → diffusion.'},
{id:"b1ocr-mcq3",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Textbook — I. Tick the Correct Choice",
 question:"The conducting tissues in plants do not include:",
 options:["vascular tissue","xylem","sclerenchyma","phloem"],correctOption:2,
 answer:"Sclerenchyma provides mechanical support but is not a conducting (vascular) tissue. Xylem and phloem are conducting tissues.",teacherTip:'Conducting = xylem + phloem (vascular).',examTip:'Sclerenchyma supports; it does not conduct water or food.'},
{id:"b1ocr-mcq4",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Textbook — I. Tick the Correct Choice",
 question:"Root hairs absorb water and minerals from the soil by:",
 options:["transpiration","ascent of sap","root pressure","osmosis"],correctOption:3,
 answer:"Water enters root hairs by osmosis through the semi-permeable cell membrane.",teacherTip:'Minerals may use active transport; water primarily by osmosis.',examTip:'Root hair water uptake → osmosis.'},
{id:"b1ocr-mcq5",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Textbook — I. Tick the Correct Choice",
 question:"The cell membrane of a plant cell is:",
 options:["permeable","semipermeable","selectively permeable","none of these"],correctOption:1,
 answer:"The plant cell membrane is semipermeable (partially permeable) — allows some substances to pass while restricting others.",teacherTip:'Semi- and selectively permeable are often used interchangeably in Class 8.',examTip:'Osmosis requires a semipermeable membrane.'},
{id:"b1ocr-mcq6",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Textbook — I. Tick the Correct Choice",
 question:"Which one of the following is a macronutrient?",
 options:["copper","boron","calcium","chlorine"],correctOption:2,
 answer:"Calcium is a macronutrient (required in large amounts). Copper, boron and chlorine are micronutrients.",teacherTip:'Macro examples: N, P, K, Ca, Mg, S.',examTip:'Macronutrients needed in large quantities.'},
{id:"b1ocr-mcq8",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Textbook — I. Tick the Correct Choice",
 question:"Prepared food material is carried through:",
 options:["xylem","vascular tissues","phloem","stomata"],correctOption:2,
 answer:"Phloem transports prepared food (sugars) from leaves to all parts of the plant (translocation).",teacherTip:'Food = phloem only.',examTip:'Prepared food → phloem.'},
{id:"b1ocr-mcq9",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Textbook — I. Tick the Correct Choice",
 question:"Water from the soil enters the root xylem by the process:",
 options:["diffusion","evaporation","osmosis","transpiration"],correctOption:2,
 answer:"Water moves from soil into root cells and eventually xylem primarily by osmosis.",teacherTip:'Transpiration pulls water up after it enters roots.',examTip:'Soil to root → osmosis.'},
{id:"b1ocr-mcq10",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Textbook — I. Tick the Correct Choice",
 question:"The loss of water through the stomata of leaves is called:",
 options:["transpiration","wilting","evaporation","osmosis"],correctOption:0,
 answer:"Transpiration is the loss of water vapour from leaves mainly through stomata.",teacherTip:'Wilting is the result of excessive water loss, not the process itself.',examTip:'Stomatal water loss = transpiration.'},
{id:"b1ocr-fb1",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Textbook — II. Fill in the Blanks",
 question:"Water passes into a root by the process called ______.",blankAnswer:"osmosis",
 answer:"Water enters root hairs from soil water by osmosis.",teacherTip:'Same answer as existing fill blank — textbook confirms it.',examTip:'Root water entry = osmosis.'},
{id:"b1ocr-fb2",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Textbook — II. Fill in the Blanks",
 question:"Osmosis occurs through a ______ membrane.",blankAnswer:"semipermeable",
 answer:"Osmosis requires a semipermeable (partially permeable) membrane.",teacherTip:'Also accept: semi-permeable.',examTip:'Spell semipermeable correctly.'},
{id:"b1ocr-fb3",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Textbook — II. Fill in the Blanks",
 question:"In osmosis, water moves from a ______ (dilute) solution into a hypertonic solution.",
 blankAnswer:"hypotonic",answer:"Water moves from a hypotonic solution (higher water concentration) into a hypertonic solution (lower water concentration).",
 teacherTip:'Hypotonic = dilute; hypertonic = concentrated cell sap.',examTip:'Hypotonic → hypertonic for water in osmosis.'},
{id:"b1ocr-fb4",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Textbook — II. Fill in the Blanks",
 question:"Upward movement of water takes place through ______ pull.",blankAnswer:"transpiration",
 answer:"Transpiration pull (suction created by water evaporation from leaves) pulls water upward through xylem.",teacherTip:'Root pressure also helps but transpiration pull is dominant.',examTip:'Ascent of sap → transpiration pull.'},
{id:"b1ocr-tf1",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Textbook — III. True or False",
 question:"In Spirogyra, transport of materials takes place through osmosis.",
 correctAnswer:"false",answer:"False. In Spirogyra, transport occurs mainly by DIFFUSION, not osmosis. Osmosis is specifically diffusion of water across a membrane.",
 teacherTip:'Spirogyra = diffusion for general transport.',examTip:'Unicellular/simple multicellular → diffusion.'},
{id:"b1ocr-tf2",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Textbook — III. True or False",
 question:"Xylem and phloem are vascular tissues.",
 correctAnswer:"true",answer:"True. Together they form the vascular (conducting) tissue system in plants.",teacherTip:'Vascular bundle contains both xylem and phloem.',examTip:'Xylem + phloem = vascular tissues.'},
{id:"b1ocr-tf3",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Textbook — III. True or False",
 question:"The girdling experiment demonstrates food synthesis in plants.",
 correctAnswer:"false",answer:"False. Girdling demonstrates TRANSPORT of food through phloem, not synthesis. Food is made in leaves by photosynthesis.",teacherTip:'Girdling blocks phloem → swelling above cut.',examTip:'Girdling = food transport proof.'},
{id:"b1ocr-tf4",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Textbook — X. Assertion-Reason",
 question:"Assertion: Roots fix the plant in the soil. Reason: Roots absorb water and minerals from soil.",
 correctAnswer:"false",answer:"Both statements are true individually, but Reason does NOT explain Assertion. Anchoring (fixing) and absorption are separate root functions — so A is true, R is true, but R is not the correct explanation of A (answer per ICSE: both true but R not correct explanation — often marked as option where A true R true but not linked).",
 teacherTip:'Roots anchor AND absorb — related but different functions.',examTip:'Assertion-reason: check if Reason actually explains Assertion.'},
{id:"b1ocr-tf5",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Textbook — X. Assertion-Reason",
 question:"Assertion: On a humid day, transpiration occurs rapidly. Reason: High temperature increases water loss.",
 correctAnswer:"false",answer:"False. On a humid day transpiration is SLOWED (high humidity reduces water loss). High temperature increases transpiration, but humidity has the opposite effect on humid days.",teacherTip:'Humid air = less transpiration.',examTip:'Humidity and transpiration are inversely related.'},
{id:"b1ocr-csq1",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Textbook — IX. Case Study",
 question:"[Case Study] The movement of water in plants is:",
 options:["bidirectional","unidirectional","multidirectional","any of these"],correctOption:1,
 answer:"Water moves unidirectionally upward through xylem (roots → stem → leaves).",teacherTip:'Food in phloem is bidirectional; water in xylem is one-way up.',examTip:'Water in xylem = unidirectional.'},
{id:"b1ocr-csq2",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Textbook — IX. Case Study",
 question:"[Case Study] Prepared food by leaves is carried through:",
 options:["phloem","xylem","parenchyma","collenchyma"],correctOption:0,
 answer:"Phloem transports food synthesised in leaves to all other plant parts.",teacherTip:'Case study reinforces xylem vs phloem roles.',examTip:'Food → phloem.'},
{id:"b1ocr-csq3",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Textbook — IX. Case Study",
 question:"[Case Study] The movement of food in phloem is:",
 options:["unidirectional","multidirectional","bidirectional","any of these"],correctOption:2,
 answer:"Food moves bidirectionally in phloem — up to growing tips and down to roots/storage.",teacherTip:'Phloem = up AND down.',examTip:'Food transport = bidirectional.'},
{id:"b1ocr-cfq1",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Textbook — XIII. Competency Questions",
 question:"P: Diffusion is the main transport in Chlamydomonas. Q: Xylem moves food upward. R: Phloem transports food from leaves. S: Diffusion suffices for all plants. Which is correct?",
 options:["P and R","Q and S","P and S","P and Q"],correctOption:0,
 answer:"P and R are correct. Q is wrong (xylem moves water, not food). S is wrong (higher plants need vascular tissues).",teacherTip:'Eliminate Q and S first.',examTip:'P + R = diffusion in simple plants + phloem for food.'},
{id:"b1ocr-cfq2",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Textbook — XIII. Competency Questions",
 question:"Which is the INCORRECTLY matched pair?",
 options:["Tracheid — Non-living elongated cell with tapering ends","Vessel — Cylindrical tube with lignified walls","Xylem parenchyma — Non-living cells for storage","Xylem fibres — Non-living thick-walled support cells"],correctOption:2,
 answer:"Xylem parenchyma consists of LIVING thin-walled cells for storage — not non-living.",teacherTip:'Only parenchyma in xylem is living.',examTip:'Xylem parenchyma = living — common trap question.'},
{id:"b1ocr-cfq3",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Textbook — XIII. Competency Questions",
 question:"Xylem (P) and phloem (Q) in plants — which is correct?",
 options:["P conducts water and minerals, Q transports food","P provides mechanical support only, Q stores fats","P stores starch, Q conducts water","P conducts hormones, Q provides support"],correctOption:0,
 answer:"Xylem conducts water and minerals upward; phloem transports food.",teacherTip:'Classic P/Q format — match function to tissue.',examTip:'P = water/minerals, Q = food.'},
{id:"b1ocr-cfq4",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Textbook — XIII. Competency Questions",
 question:"Which is NOT a characteristic of phloem tissue?",
 options:["Consists of both living and non-living cells","Sieve tubes lack nucleus at maturity","Companion cells help in conduction of water and minerals","Sieve plates have pores for food passage"],correctOption:2,
 answer:"Companion cells assist FOOD conduction in phloem, not water and minerals (that is xylem\'s role).",teacherTip:'Companion cells partner with sieve tubes for food transport.',examTip:'Water/minerals = xylem, never companion cells.'},
{id:"b1ocr-sa1",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Textbook — VIII. Answer the Questions",
 question:"Name the two tissues responsible for transporting food and water in higher plants.",
 answer:"XYLEM transports water and dissolved mineral salts.\nPHLOEM transports prepared food (sugars) from leaves to other parts.",teacherTip:'Two tissues — one line each.',examTip:'Xylem = water; Phloem = food.'},
{id:"b1ocr-sa2",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Textbook — VIII. Answer the Questions",
 question:"How does transport of materials take place in unicellular plants?",
 answer:"In unicellular plants like Chlamydomonas, transport occurs by DIFFUSION — net movement of molecules from higher to lower concentration until evenly spread.",teacherTip:'No xylem/phloem in unicellular plants.',examTip:'Unicellular → diffusion only.'},
{id:"b1ocr-sa3",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Textbook — VIII. Answer the Questions",
 question:"What are root hairs? Mention the function performed by root hairs.",
 answer:"Root hairs are unicellular, thin-walled outgrowths of the root epidermis just behind the root tip.\n\nFunction: They greatly increase the surface area for absorption of water and mineral salts from the soil.",teacherTip:'More surface area = faster absorption.',examTip:'Define structure + absorption function.'},
{id:"b1ocr-sa4",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Textbook — VIII. Answer the Questions",
 question:"How does movement and absorption of water take place through the roots?",
 answer:"Soil water enters root hair cells by OSMOSIS (semipermeable membrane). Water then passes from cell to cell and enters the xylem. Upward movement continues via root pressure and transpiration pull through xylem vessels.",teacherTip:'Absorption (osmosis) then conduction (xylem).',examTip:'Mention osmosis at root hairs + xylem conduction.'},
{id:"b1ocr-sa5",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Textbook — VIII. Answer the Questions",
 question:"Differentiate between osmosis and transpiration.",
 answer:"OSMOSIS: Movement of water through a semipermeable membrane from higher to lower water concentration. Occurs at root cells during water absorption. No energy needed.\n\nTRANSPIRATION: Loss of water vapour from aerial parts (mainly stomata of leaves). Creates transpiration pull for upward water movement. Also cools the plant.",teacherTip:'Osmosis = water IN at roots. Transpiration = water OUT at leaves.',examTip:'Compare process, location, and role.'},
{id:"b1ocr-sa6",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Textbook — VIII. Answer the Questions",
 question:"Differentiate between micronutrients and macronutrients.",
 answer:"MACRONUTRIENTS: Required in LARGE quantities. Examples: nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, calcium, magnesium, sulphur.\n\nMICRONUTRIENTS (trace elements): Required in VERY SMALL amounts. Examples: iron, copper, zinc, boron, manganese, molybdenum, chlorine.",teacherTip:'Macro = big amount; Micro = trace.',examTip:'Give definition + two examples of each.'},
{id:"b1ocr-sa7",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Textbook — VIII. Answer the Questions",
 question:"How does transpiration help in the uptake of water from the soil?",
 answer:"Transpiration removes water from leaves, creating a transpiration PULL (suction). This pull draws water continuously upward through the xylem from roots, which in turn draws more water into roots from the soil by osmosis.",teacherTip:'Chain: transpiration → pull → xylem flow → root osmosis.',examTip:'Transpiration pull links leaf loss to root uptake.'},
{id:"b1ocr-sa8",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Textbook — VIII. Answer the Questions",
 question:"List four features outlining the importance of minerals in plant life.",
 answer:"1. Essential for healthy growth and development.\n2. Provide nutrition to plants.\n3. Without minerals, vegetative or reproductive phases cannot complete.\n4. Deficiency causes specific disorders (e.g. chlorosis) correctable only by supplying that mineral.",teacherTip:'Link minerals to growth + deficiency diseases.',examTip:'At least four distinct importance points.'},
{id:"b1ocr-sa9",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Textbook — VI. Odd One Out",
 question:"Find the odd one out, giving reason: Sieve tube, tracheid, companion cell, phloem fibre.",
 answer:"Odd one out: TRACHEID.\nReason: Tracheid is a xylem element (conducts water). The others — sieve tube, companion cell, and phloem fibre — are phloem components (food transport).",teacherTip:'Tracheid = xylem; rest = phloem.',examTip:'State odd term + which tissue group it belongs to.'},
{id:"b1ocr-sa10",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Textbook — VI. Odd One Out",
 question:"Find the odd one out, giving reason: Tracheids, vessels, xylem fibres, companion cells.",
 answer:"Odd one out: COMPANION CELL.\nReason: Companion cell is part of phloem (living, assists food transport). Tracheids, vessels, and xylem fibres are xylem elements.",teacherTip:'Companion cell always pairs with sieve tubes in phloem.',examTip:'Odd term from opposite tissue.'},
{id:"b1ocr-sa11",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Textbook — VII. Identify the Following",
 question:"Identify: A method by which transport of materials occurs in unicellular plants.",
 answer:"DIFFUSION — net movement of molecules from higher to lower concentration.",teacherTip:'One word answer expected.',examTip:'Unicellular transport = diffusion.'},
{id:"b1ocr-sa12",topicId:"bio-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Textbook — VII. Identify the Following",
 question:"Identify: The term used to describe yellowing of leaves.",
 answer:"CHLOROSIS — yellowing of leaves due to loss of chlorophyll, often caused by nitrogen or magnesium deficiency.",teacherTip:'Chlorosis ≠ wilting (drooping).',examTip:'Yellow leaves → chlorosis.'},

// ======================== CH2: REPRODUCTION IN PLANTS ========================
{id:"b2n1",topicId:"bio-ch2",type:"note",subtopic:"Types of Reproduction",content:'Plants reproduce by two methods: (1) ASEXUAL REPRODUCTION — new plant from a single parent without seeds (e.g., budding, fragmentation, vegetative propagation, spore formation). (2) SEXUAL REPRODUCTION — involves fusion of male and female gametes, usually produces seeds.',explanation:'Asexual = clone of parent (identical). Sexual = mix of two parents (variation). Both have advantages in different situations.',teacherTip:'Asexual = one parent, identical offspring. Sexual = two parents, varied offspring.',examTip:'Give examples for each type when asked to differentiate.'},
{id:"b2n2",topicId:"bio-ch2",type:"note",subtopic:"Parts of a Flower",content:'A typical flower has 4 whorls: (1) SEPALS (calyx) — protect the bud. (2) PETALS (corolla) — attract pollinators with colour/scent. (3) STAMENS (androecium) — male part, produces pollen in anthers. (4) PISTIL/CARPEL (gynoecium) — female part, has stigma, style, and ovary containing ovules.',explanation:'The stamen (male) makes pollen grains. The pistil (female) contains egg cells in ovules. When pollen reaches the stigma, fertilization can begin.',teacherTip:'Remember: "Stamen = Stamina = Male strength" and "Pistil = Female."',examTip:'Draw and label a flower diagram — it appears in almost every exam.'},
{id:"b2n3",topicId:"bio-ch2",type:"note",subtopic:"Pollination and Fertilization",content:'POLLINATION: Transfer of pollen from anther to stigma. Self-pollination = same flower. Cross-pollination = different flower (by wind, insects, water, birds). FERTILIZATION: Pollen tube grows down the style, male gamete fuses with egg cell in the ovule. After fertilization: ovule → seed, ovary → fruit.',explanation:'Pollination is just delivery of pollen. Fertilization is the actual fusion. After fertilization, the ovary swells to become the fruit protecting the seeds inside.',teacherTip:'Pollination = postal delivery. Fertilization = opening the letter (fusion).',examTip:'Clearly distinguish pollination from fertilization — they are NOT the same thing.'},
{id:"b2n4",topicId:"bio-ch2",type:"note",subtopic:"Seed Dispersal",content:'Seeds must be scattered away from parent plant to reduce competition. Methods: (1) WIND — light seeds with wings/parachutes (dandelion, maple). (2) WATER — seeds that float (coconut). (3) ANIMALS — hooks/spines that stick to fur, or fleshy fruits eaten by animals. (4) EXPLOSION — pods burst open to fling seeds (pea, balsam).',explanation:'If all seeds fell directly under the parent tree, they would compete for sunlight, water, and nutrients. Dispersal gives each seed a better chance of survival.',teacherTip:'Each dispersal method matches the seed\'s structure — hooks for animals, wings for wind.',examTip:'Give one example for each method of seed dispersal.'},
// TRUE/FALSE
{id:"b2tf1",topicId:"bio-ch2",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The__(stamen) is the female reproductive part of a flower.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:"False. The stamen is the MALE part (produces pollen). The PISTIL (carpel) is the female part.",teacherTip:'Stamen = Male. Pistil = Female. A very common trick question!',examTip:'If confused, remember: Pistil has the ovary which produces eggs (female).'},
{id:"b2tf2",topicId:"bio-ch2",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"After fertilization, the ovary develops into a fruit.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:"True. The ovary wall becomes the fruit wall, and the ovules inside become seeds.",teacherTip:'Ovary → Fruit. Ovule → Seed. Simple transformation!',examTip:'State both transformations (ovary→fruit AND ovule→seed) for complete answers.'},
{id:"b2tf3",topicId:"bio-ch2",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Cross-pollination occurs when pollen is transferred within the same flower.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:"False. That is SELF-pollination. CROSS-pollination is transfer of pollen from one flower to another flower (of the same species).",teacherTip:'Cross = across different flowers. Self = same flower.',examTip:'Define both self and cross-pollination when asked about either one.'},
// FILL BLANKS
{id:"b2fb1",topicId:"bio-ch2",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The male part of a flower is called ______.",blankAnswer:"stamen",answer:"The stamen consists of the anther (which produces pollen) and the filament (which supports the anther).",teacherTip:'The anther is like a pollen factory sitting on top of a stalk (filament).',examTip:'Name both parts of the stamen (anther + filament) for extra marks.'},
{id:"b2fb2",topicId:"bio-ch2",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"After fertilization, the ovule develops into a ______.",blankAnswer:"seed",answer:"The ovule contains the egg cell. After fertilization (fusion with male gamete), the ovule develops into a seed containing the embryo.",teacherTip:'Ovule → Seed. The embryo inside the seed is the baby plant!',examTip:'Mention that the seed contains an embryo (future plant).'},
// MCQ
{id:"b2mcq1",topicId:"bio-ch2",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Which part of the flower develops into fruit?",options:["Sepal","Petal","Ovary","Anther"],correctOption:2,answer:"The ovary develops into the fruit after fertilization. The ovary wall becomes the fruit wall (pericarp).",teacherTip:'Ovary = future fruit. Think of ovary as "fruit-in-waiting."',examTip:'Mention "after fertilization" to show the cause-effect relationship.'},
{id:"b2mcq2",topicId:"bio-ch2",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Dandelion seeds are dispersed by:",options:["Water","Animals","Wind","Explosion"],correctOption:2,answer:"Dandelion seeds have light, feathery parachute-like structures that help them float in the wind over long distances.",teacherTip:'Dandelions blow in the wind — classic wind dispersal!',examTip:'Describe the structural adaptation (parachute/wings) that aids wind dispersal.'},
// SHORT ANSWER
{id:"b2sa1",topicId:"bio-ch2",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Draw a labelled diagram of a flower and name its four main whorls.",answer:'The four whorls of a flower (from outside to inside):\n\n1. CALYX (Sepals) — Green, leaf-like, protects the flower bud\n2. COROLLA (Petals) — Colourful, attracts pollinators\n3. ANDROECIUM (Stamens) — Male part, each stamen has anther + filament\n4. GYNOECIUM (Pistil/Carpel) — Female part, has stigma + style + ovary\n\nThe ovary contains ovules which become seeds after fertilization.',teacherTip:'Draw from outside in: Sepals → Petals → Stamens → Pistil (center).',examTip:'Label at least 6 parts: sepal, petal, anther, filament, stigma, ovary.'},

// ======================== CH3: REPRODUCTION IN HUMANS ========================
{id:"b3n1",topicId:"bio-ch3",type:"note",subtopic:"Human Reproductive System",content:'Humans reproduce sexually. MALE system: Testes produce sperm and testosterone. Sperm travel through vas deferens. FEMALE system: Ovaries produce eggs (ova) and hormones (estrogen, progesterone). Eggs travel through fallopian tubes (oviducts) to the uterus. Fertilization occurs in the fallopian tube.',explanation:'The male produces millions of tiny sperm. The female produces one egg per month. When a sperm meets the egg and fuses with it, fertilization occurs and a new life begins.',teacherTip:'Testes = sperm factory. Ovaries = egg factory. Fallopian tube = meeting point.',examTip:'Name the organs AND their functions for complete answers.'},
{id:"b3n2",topicId:"bio-ch3",type:"note",subtopic:"Fertilization and Development",content:'FERTILIZATION: Fusion of sperm and egg to form a ZYGOTE in the fallopian tube. The zygote divides repeatedly to form an EMBRYO, which implants in the uterus wall. The PLACENTA provides oxygen and nutrients from mother\'s blood to the embryo (now called FOETUS). After about 9 months (gestation period), the baby is born.',explanation:'The placenta acts as a bridge between mother and baby — exchanging nutrients, oxygen, and waste WITHOUT mixing their blood directly.',teacherTip:'Zygote → Embryo → Foetus → Baby. Each stage has a specific name.',examTip:'Define: zygote, embryo, foetus, placenta, and gestation period.'},
// TRUE/FALSE
{id:"b3tf1",topicId:"bio-ch3",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Fertilization in humans occurs in the uterus.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:"False. Fertilization occurs in the FALLOPIAN TUBE (oviduct). The fertilized egg (zygote) then travels to the uterus for implantation.",teacherTip:'Fallopian tube = fertilization. Uterus = implantation and growth.',examTip:'This is a very common trick question — fertilization is NOT in the uterus.'},
{id:"b3tf2",topicId:"bio-ch3",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The placenta provides nutrients to the developing embryo.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:"True. The placenta is a disc-shaped organ that connects the foetus to the mother\'s uterine wall. It transfers oxygen and nutrients from mother to foetus, and removes waste from foetus to mother.",teacherTip:'Placenta = lifeline between mother and baby.',examTip:'Mention that mother\'s blood and baby\'s blood do NOT mix directly.'},
// MCQ
{id:"b3mcq1",topicId:"bio-ch3",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The fusion of sperm and egg is called:",options:["Pollination","Germination","Fertilization","Ovulation"],correctOption:2,answer:"Fertilization is the fusion of the male gamete (sperm) with the female gamete (egg/ovum) to form a zygote.",teacherTip:'Fertilization = fusion. Pollination is only in plants!',examTip:'Never use "pollination" for humans — that\'s only for flowers.'},
// SHORT ANSWER
{id:"b3sa1",topicId:"bio-ch3",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"What is the role of the placenta during pregnancy?",answer:'The PLACENTA is a temporary organ that connects the developing foetus to the mother\'s uterine wall. Its functions:\n\n1. Supplies oxygen and nutrients from mother\'s blood to the foetus\n2. Removes carbon dioxide and waste products from the foetus to the mother\n3. Acts as a barrier — prevents mixing of mother\'s and baby\'s blood\n4. Produces hormones to maintain pregnancy\n\nThe foetus is connected to the placenta through the UMBILICAL CORD.',teacherTip:'Placenta = exchange centre + protective barrier + hormone factory.',examTip:'Mention the umbilical cord as the physical connection between foetus and placenta.'},

// ======================== CH4: ECOSYSTEMS ========================
{id:"b4n1",topicId:"bio-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"Ecosystem Basics",content:'An ECOSYSTEM is a community of living organisms (biotic) interacting with their non-living environment (abiotic). Biotic factors: plants, animals, microorganisms. Abiotic factors: sunlight, water, temperature, soil, air. Types: forest, grassland, desert, aquatic (freshwater and marine).',explanation:'An ecosystem is like a neighbourhood where everyone (plants, animals, fungi, bacteria) depends on each other and shares resources like water, light, and space.',teacherTip:'Biotic = Bio = Life. Abiotic = A (not) + biotic = non-living.',examTip:'Always give examples of both biotic AND abiotic factors when defining ecosystem.'},
{id:"b4n2",topicId:"bio-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"Food Chains and Food Webs",content:'A FOOD CHAIN shows the flow of energy from one organism to another. Starts with PRODUCERS (green plants) → PRIMARY CONSUMERS (herbivores) → SECONDARY CONSUMERS (carnivores) → TERTIARY CONSUMERS (top predators). A FOOD WEB is many interconnected food chains in an ecosystem. Energy decreases at each level (10% rule).',explanation:'Plants capture sun\'s energy. Herbivores eat plants. Carnivores eat herbivores. At each step, about 90% of energy is lost as heat, so only 10% passes to the next level.',teacherTip:'Food chain = single line. Food web = tangled network. Web is more realistic.',examTip:'Always start a food chain with a PRODUCER (green plant). Use arrows pointing in the direction energy flows.'},
{id:"b4n3",topicId:"bio-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"Decomposers and Nutrient Cycling",content:'DECOMPOSERS (bacteria, fungi) break down dead organisms and waste into simple nutrients that return to the soil. This is essential for NUTRIENT CYCLING — carbon, nitrogen, and other elements are recycled between living and non-living parts of the ecosystem. Without decomposers, dead matter would pile up and nutrients would be locked away.',explanation:'Decomposers are nature\'s recyclers. They close the loop in an ecosystem by returning nutrients to the soil so plants can use them again.',teacherTip:'Decomposers = cleanup crew. Without them, Earth would be covered in dead things!',examTip:'Name bacteria and fungi as the two main types of decomposers.'},
// TRUE/FALSE
{id:"b4tf1",topicId:"bio-ch4",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A food chain always begins with a producer.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:"True. Producers (green plants) are always the first link in a food chain because they convert solar energy into food through photosynthesis.",teacherTip:'No producers = no food chain. Plants are the foundation of every ecosystem.',examTip:'Draw arrows FROM the producer TOWARD consumers (direction of energy flow).'},
{id:"b4tf2",topicId:"bio-ch4",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Energy increases as we move up a food chain.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:"False. Energy DECREASES at each trophic level. Only about 10% of energy passes from one level to the next. The rest is lost as heat.",teacherTip:'The 10% rule — each level gets only 10% of the previous level\'s energy.',examTip:'Explain the 10% rule when discussing energy flow in food chains.'},
// MCQ
{id:"b4mcq1",topicId:"bio-ch4",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Which of the following is a decomposer?",options:["Eagle","Deer","Mushroom","Grass"],correctOption:2,answer:"Mushrooms (fungi) are decomposers. They break down dead organic matter into simpler substances, recycling nutrients back into the soil.",teacherTip:'Fungi and bacteria = decomposers. They feed on dead and decaying matter.',examTip:'Common decomposers to remember: bacteria, fungi (mushrooms), earthworms.'},
// SHORT ANSWER
{id:"b4sa1",topicId:"bio-ch4",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"What is a food web? How is it different from a food chain?",answer:'FOOD CHAIN: A linear sequence showing the transfer of energy from one organism to the next.\nExample: Grass → Grasshopper → Frog → Snake → Eagle\n\nFOOD WEB: A complex network of many interconnected food chains in an ecosystem. It shows that most organisms eat more than one type of food and are eaten by more than one predator.\n\nDifference: A food chain is a single pathway; a food web shows ALL the feeding relationships. Food webs are more realistic because organisms rarely depend on just one food source.',teacherTip:'A food web is like a "food internet" — everything is connected to everything else.',examTip:'Always give a specific food chain example when asked about food chains or webs.'},

// ======================== CH5: ENDOCRINE SYSTEM & ADOLESCENCE ========================
{id:"b5n1",topicId:"bio-ch5",type:"note",subtopic:"Endocrine Glands",content:'The ENDOCRINE SYSTEM consists of ductless glands that secrete HORMONES directly into the blood. Major glands: PITUITARY (master gland — controls other glands), THYROID (thyroxine — controls metabolism), PANCREAS (insulin — controls blood sugar), ADRENAL (adrenaline — fight-or-flight response). Hormones are chemical messengers that regulate body functions.',explanation:'Unlike sweat glands that have ducts (tubes), endocrine glands release hormones directly into the bloodstream. Blood carries hormones to target organs throughout the body.',teacherTip:'Endocrine = Ductless = directly into blood. Exocrine = has ducts (like sweat, saliva).',examTip:'Know at least 4 glands with their hormones AND functions.'},
{id:"b5n2",topicId:"bio-ch5",type:"note",subtopic:"Adolescence & Puberty",content:'ADOLESCENCE is the period between childhood and adulthood (roughly ages 11-19). PUBERTY is the onset of sexual maturity when the body changes under the influence of hormones. Changes in boys: facial hair, deeper voice, muscle growth (testosterone). Changes in girls: breast development, menstruation begins, hip widening (estrogen). Common changes: growth spurt, acne, mood changes.',explanation:'The pituitary gland signals the testes (boys) and ovaries (girls) to start producing sex hormones, which trigger all the physical changes of puberty.',teacherTip:'Pituitary gland starts puberty by sending signals to reproductive organs.',examTip:'List changes separately for boys and girls, plus common changes shared by both.'},
// TRUE/FALSE
{id:"b5tf1",topicId:"bio-ch5",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The pituitary gland is called the master gland.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:"True. The pituitary gland is called the master gland because it controls the functioning of most other endocrine glands by releasing stimulating hormones.",teacherTip:'Pituitary = boss gland. It tells other glands what to do.',examTip:'Explain WHY it\'s called "master gland" — because it controls other glands.'},
{id:"b5tf2",topicId:"bio-ch5",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Insulin is produced by the thyroid gland.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:"False. Insulin is produced by the PANCREAS. The thyroid gland produces thyroxine, which controls metabolism.",teacherTip:'Pancreas → Insulin → Blood sugar. Thyroid → Thyroxine → Metabolism.',examTip:'Know which hormone comes from which gland — very commonly tested.'},
// MCQ
{id:"b5mcq1",topicId:"bio-ch5",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Which hormone controls blood sugar levels?",options:["Thyroxine","Adrenaline","Insulin","Growth hormone"],correctOption:2,answer:"Insulin (from the pancreas) lowers blood sugar by allowing cells to take in glucose. Deficiency causes diabetes.",teacherTip:'Insulin = "key" that opens cell doors for sugar to enter.',examTip:'Mention "diabetes" as the disease caused by insulin deficiency.'},
// SHORT ANSWER
{id:"b5sa1",topicId:"bio-ch5",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Name four major endocrine glands and their hormones with one function each.",answer:'1. PITUITARY GLAND → Growth Hormone → Controls body growth\n2. THYROID GLAND → Thyroxine → Controls rate of metabolism\n3. PANCREAS → Insulin → Lowers blood sugar level\n4. ADRENAL GLAND → Adrenaline → Prepares body for emergency (fight-or-flight)\n5. TESTES (male) → Testosterone → Development of male features\n6. OVARIES (female) → Estrogen → Development of female features',teacherTip:'Make a table: Gland | Hormone | Function — easy to remember.',examTip:'Learn at least 5 gland-hormone-function combos for the exam.'},

// ======================== CH6: THE CIRCULATORY SYSTEM ========================
{id:"b6n1",topicId:"bio-ch6",type:"note",subtopic:"Heart and Blood Circulation",content:'The HEART is a muscular organ with 4 chambers: 2 atria (upper, receive blood) and 2 ventricles (lower, pump blood out). RIGHT side pumps deoxygenated blood to lungs (pulmonary circulation). LEFT side pumps oxygenated blood to body (systemic circulation). This is called DOUBLE CIRCULATION — blood passes through the heart twice in one complete circuit.',explanation:'The heart is actually two pumps side by side. The right pump sends blood to lungs to get oxygen. The left pump sends oxygen-rich blood to the entire body.',teacherTip:'Right = Lungs (to collect O₂). Left = Body (to deliver O₂). Remember: Right-Lung, Left-Body.',examTip:'Use the term "double circulation" and explain both pulmonary and systemic circuits.'},
{id:"b6n2",topicId:"bio-ch6",type:"note",subtopic:"Blood Components",content:'BLOOD has 4 components: (1) RED BLOOD CELLS (RBCs) — contain haemoglobin, carry oxygen. (2) WHITE BLOOD CELLS (WBCs) — fight infections (immunity). (3) PLATELETS — help in blood clotting at wound sites. (4) PLASMA — liquid part (55% of blood), carries dissolved nutrients, hormones, waste, and proteins.',explanation:'Blood is like a delivery service: RBCs deliver oxygen, plasma delivers food and hormones, WBCs are the security team, and platelets are the repair crew.',teacherTip:'RBC = oxygen taxi. WBC = soldiers. Platelets = band-aids. Plasma = river everything floats in.',examTip:'Name all 4 components with their functions for full marks.'},
// TRUE/FALSE
{id:"b6tf1",topicId:"bio-ch6",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Arteries carry oxygenated blood away from the heart.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:"True (with one exception). Arteries carry oxygenated blood FROM heart TO body. Exception: Pulmonary artery carries deoxygenated blood from heart to lungs.",teacherTip:'Arteries = Away from heart. Veins = toward heart (Veins = in).',examTip:'ALWAYS mention the exception (pulmonary artery) to show thorough knowledge.'},
{id:"b6tf2",topicId:"bio-ch6",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"White blood cells carry oxygen in the blood.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:"False. RED blood cells (RBCs) carry oxygen using haemoglobin. WHITE blood cells (WBCs) fight infections and provide immunity.",teacherTip:'Red = oxygen. White = defence. Don\'t mix them up!',examTip:'Mention "haemoglobin" when talking about oxygen transport by RBCs.'},
// MCQ
{id:"b6mcq1",topicId:"bio-ch6",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"How many chambers does the human heart have?",options:["2","3","4","5"],correctOption:2,answer:"The human heart has 4 chambers: 2 atria (upper) and 2 ventricles (lower). The septum divides the heart into left and right halves.",teacherTip:'4 chambers = 2 atria + 2 ventricles. Septum keeps oxygenated and deoxygenated blood separate.',examTip:'Name all 4 chambers: left atrium, right atrium, left ventricle, right ventricle.'},
// SHORT ANSWER
{id:"b6sa1",topicId:"bio-ch6",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"What is double circulation? Explain with a diagram description.",answer:'DOUBLE CIRCULATION means blood passes through the heart TWICE in one complete cycle.\n\n1. PULMONARY CIRCULATION (Right side):\nRight ventricle → Pulmonary artery → Lungs (picks up O₂, drops CO₂) → Pulmonary vein → Left atrium\n\n2. SYSTEMIC CIRCULATION (Left side):\nLeft ventricle → Aorta → Body organs (delivers O₂, picks up CO₂) → Vena cava → Right atrium\n\nAdvantage: Oxygenated blood reaches body at high pressure, ensuring efficient delivery of oxygen to all tissues.',teacherTip:'Right side = lung circuit. Left side = body circuit. Blood visits heart twice!',examTip:'Draw the flow as: Body → Right heart → Lungs → Left heart → Body.'},

// ======================== CH7: NERVOUS SYSTEM ========================
{id:"b7n1",topicId:"bio-ch7",type:"note",subtopic:"Nervous System Overview",content:'The NERVOUS SYSTEM controls and coordinates all body activities. It has 3 parts: (1) CENTRAL NERVOUS SYSTEM (CNS) = Brain + Spinal cord. (2) PERIPHERAL NERVOUS SYSTEM (PNS) = Nerves connecting CNS to all body parts. (3) AUTONOMIC NERVOUS SYSTEM = Controls involuntary actions (heartbeat, digestion). The basic unit is the NEURON (nerve cell).',explanation:'The brain is like the CEO, the spinal cord is the highway, and nerves are roads connecting every part of the body to headquarters.',teacherTip:'CNS = command centre. PNS = communication wires. Autonomic = autopilot.',examTip:'Name all 3 divisions of the nervous system for a complete answer.'},
{id:"b7n2",topicId:"bio-ch7",type:"note",subtopic:"The Brain",content:'The brain has 3 main parts: (1) CEREBRUM — largest part, controls thinking, memory, reasoning, voluntary actions, and senses. (2) CEREBELLUM — behind cerebrum, controls balance, posture, and coordination of movements. (3) MEDULLA OBLONGATA — base of brain, controls involuntary actions like breathing, heartbeat, swallowing, and blood pressure.',explanation:'Cerebrum = thinking brain (biggest). Cerebellum = balance brain (behind). Medulla = survival brain (bottom) — controls things you don\'t think about.',teacherTip:'"Cerebrum = Cerebral = Thinking. Cerebellum = Balance (like a ballerina). Medulla = Must-do (breathing, heartbeat)."',examTip:'Know at least 2 functions for each part of the brain.'},
{id:"b7n3",topicId:"bio-ch7",type:"note",subtopic:"Reflex Action",content:'A REFLEX ACTION is an automatic, rapid, involuntary response to a stimulus. Example: pulling hand away from a hot object. The pathway is called a REFLEX ARC: Receptor → Sensory nerve → Spinal cord → Motor nerve → Effector (muscle/gland). Reflexes are controlled by the SPINAL CORD, not the brain — this makes them faster.',explanation:'When you touch something hot, you pull your hand away BEFORE you even feel the pain. The spinal cord handles the response immediately without waiting for the brain.',teacherTip:'Reflex = shortcut through spinal cord. Brain finds out AFTER the action!',examTip:'Draw the reflex arc and label all 5 components for full marks.'},
// TRUE/FALSE
{id:"b7tf1",topicId:"bio-ch7",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Reflex actions are controlled by the brain.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:"False. Reflex actions are controlled by the SPINAL CORD. This makes them faster because the signal doesn\'t need to travel all the way to the brain.",teacherTip:'Reflexes bypass the brain — spinal cord handles them directly.',examTip:'Mention "speed" as the advantage of spinal cord control.'},
{id:"b7tf2",topicId:"bio-ch7",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The cerebellum controls balance and coordination.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:"True. The cerebellum maintains body balance, posture, and coordinates precise voluntary movements like writing, typing, or catching a ball.",teacherTip:'Cerebellum = "little brain" at the back = balance + coordination.',examTip:'Give examples of actions controlled by cerebellum (walking, cycling, catching).'},
// MCQ
{id:"b7mcq1",topicId:"bio-ch7",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Which part of the brain controls involuntary actions like breathing?",options:["Cerebrum","Cerebellum","Medulla oblongata","Spinal cord"],correctOption:2,answer:"The medulla oblongata controls vital involuntary functions: breathing, heartbeat, blood pressure, swallowing, coughing, and sneezing.",teacherTip:'Medulla = "autopilot" for survival. Damage here is life-threatening.',examTip:'List at least 3 involuntary actions controlled by the medulla.'},
// SHORT ANSWER
{id:"b7sa1",topicId:"bio-ch7",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"What is a reflex action? Describe the reflex arc with an example.",answer:'REFLEX ACTION: An automatic, quick, involuntary response to a stimulus, controlled by the spinal cord.\n\nExample: Touching a hot object and pulling hand away.\n\nREFLEX ARC pathway:\n1. RECEPTOR (skin) — detects the hot stimulus\n2. SENSORY NERVE — carries impulse from receptor to spinal cord\n3. SPINAL CORD — processes the information and generates response\n4. MOTOR NERVE — carries impulse from spinal cord to effector\n5. EFFECTOR (muscle) — contracts and pulls the hand away\n\nAdvantage: Protects the body from harm by responding faster than conscious thought.',teacherTip:'5 steps: Receptor → Sensory → Spinal cord → Motor → Effector. Learn the order!',examTip:'Drawing the reflex arc as a diagram scores higher than just writing text.'},

// ======================== CH8: DISEASES AND FIRST AID ========================
{id:"b8n1",topicId:"bio-ch8",type:"note",subtopic:"Types of Diseases",content:'Diseases are classified as: (1) COMMUNICABLE (infectious) — caused by microorganisms, can spread person to person. Examples: malaria (protozoa), tuberculosis (bacteria), common cold (virus), ringworm (fungi). (2) NON-COMMUNICABLE — cannot spread, caused by lifestyle/genetics. Examples: diabetes, cancer, heart disease, allergies.',explanation:'Communicable diseases have a pathogen (germ) that can travel from one person to another through air, water, food, or contact. Non-communicable diseases stay with the person.',teacherTip:'Communicable = Catching = Contagious. Non-communicable = Not catching.',examTip:'Give the causative organism for each communicable disease you mention.'},
{id:"b8n2",topicId:"bio-ch8",type:"note",subtopic:"Modes of Disease Transmission",content:'Communicable diseases spread through: (1) AIR — coughing/sneezing (cold, TB, flu). (2) WATER — contaminated drinking water (cholera, typhoid). (3) FOOD — unhygienic food (food poisoning, dysentery). (4) CONTACT — direct touching or body fluids (ringworm, AIDS). (5) VECTORS — organisms that carry disease (mosquitoes carry malaria and dengue, houseflies carry cholera).',explanation:'A vector is an organism that doesn\'t cause the disease itself but carries the pathogen from an infected person to a healthy person. Mosquitoes are the most dangerous vectors.',teacherTip:'A vector is a "disease taxi" — it gives the germ a ride to its next victim.',examTip:'Name the vector AND the disease it carries (e.g., female Anopheles mosquito → malaria).'},
{id:"b8n3",topicId:"bio-ch8",type:"note",subtopic:"First Aid Basics",content:'FIRST AID is the immediate help given to an injured or sick person before medical help arrives. Key principles: (1) BURNS — cool with running water for 10+ minutes. (2) BLEEDING — apply firm pressure with clean cloth, raise the wound. (3) FRACTURES — immobilize the area, don\'t try to set the bone. (4) INSECT STINGS — remove stinger, apply cold compress. (5) FAINTING — lay person flat, raise legs, ensure fresh air.',explanation:'First aid is about stabilizing the person, not curing them. The goal is to prevent the condition from getting worse until a doctor takes over.',teacherTip:'Remember: DON\'T panic, DON\'T move fractures, DON\'T apply ice directly on burns.',examTip:'For each injury, state what TO do and what NOT to do.'},
// TRUE/FALSE
{id:"b8tf1",topicId:"bio-ch8",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Malaria is caused by a virus.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:"False. Malaria is caused by a PROTOZOAN parasite called Plasmodium. It is transmitted by the bite of an infected female Anopheles mosquito.",teacherTip:'Malaria = Plasmodium (protozoa) via Anopheles mosquito. Not a virus!',examTip:'Name both the causative organism AND the vector for malaria.'},
{id:"b8tf2",topicId:"bio-ch8",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Non-communicable diseases can spread from person to person.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:"False. Non-communicable diseases (like diabetes, cancer, heart disease) CANNOT spread from person to person. They are caused by genetics, lifestyle, or environmental factors.",teacherTip:'Non-communicable = Non-contagious. They stay with the individual.',examTip:'Give 2-3 examples of non-communicable diseases in your answer.'},
// MCQ
{id:"b8mcq1",topicId:"bio-ch8",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Which organism transmits malaria?",options:["Housefly","Male Anopheles mosquito","Female Anopheles mosquito","Cockroach"],correctOption:2,answer:"The FEMALE Anopheles mosquito transmits malaria. Only females bite (they need blood for egg development). The male Anopheles feeds on plant nectar.",teacherTip:'Only FEMALE Anopheles bites. Male mosquitoes are vegetarians!',examTip:'Specify "female" Anopheles — writing just "Anopheles mosquito" may lose marks.'},
// SHORT ANSWER
{id:"b8sa1",topicId:"bio-ch8",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Differentiate between communicable and non-communicable diseases. Give two examples of each.",answer:'COMMUNICABLE DISEASES:\n• Caused by pathogens (bacteria, virus, fungi, protozoa)\n• CAN spread from person to person\n• Spread through air, water, food, contact, or vectors\n• Examples: Malaria (protozoa), Tuberculosis (bacteria), Common cold (virus)\n\nNON-COMMUNICABLE DISEASES:\n• NOT caused by pathogens\n• CANNOT spread from person to person\n• Caused by genetics, lifestyle, diet, or environmental factors\n• Examples: Diabetes, Cancer, Heart disease, Allergies',teacherTip:'Communicable = germ + spread. Non-communicable = no germ + no spread.',examTip:'Compare at least 4 features and give 2+ examples for each type.'},

// ======================== CH9: FOOD PRODUCTION ========================
{id:"b9n1",topicId:"bio-ch9",type:"note",subtopic:"Crop Production",content:'AGRICULTURE is the science of cultivating land, growing crops, and raising livestock. Steps in crop production: (1) PREPARATION OF SOIL — ploughing, levelling. (2) SOWING — planting seeds at correct depth and spacing. (3) ADDING MANURE/FERTILIZERS — for nutrients. (4) IRRIGATION — supplying water. (5) WEEDING — removing unwanted plants. (6) HARVESTING — collecting mature crops. (7) STORAGE — protecting from moisture, pests.',explanation:'Farming is a step-by-step process. Each step matters — wrong seed depth, too little water, or pest damage can ruin an entire harvest.',teacherTip:'Remember the order: Prepare → Sow → Nourish → Water → Weed → Harvest → Store.',examTip:'List all 7 steps in order when asked about crop production practices.'},
{id:"b9n2",topicId:"bio-ch9",type:"note",subtopic:"Manure vs Fertilizers",content:'MANURE: Natural, organic material made from decomposed plant/animal waste (compost, farmyard manure). Improves soil structure, adds humus, slow-release nutrients. FERTILIZERS: Chemical/synthetic substances (NPK — Nitrogen, Phosphorus, Potassium). Quick-release, specific nutrient supply, but can harm soil health if overused.',explanation:'Manure is like a balanced home-cooked meal for the soil. Fertilizers are like supplements — fast-acting but can cause problems if used too much (soil pollution, water contamination).',teacherTip:'Manure = natural + slow + improves soil. Fertilizer = chemical + fast + can damage soil.',examTip:'Compare at least 4 differences between manure and fertilizers.'},
{id:"b9n3",topicId:"bio-ch9",type:"note",subtopic:"Animal Husbandry",content:'ANIMAL HUSBANDRY is the scientific management of livestock for food and other products. Includes: DAIRY FARMING (milk, cheese, butter), POULTRY FARMING (eggs, chicken meat), FISH FARMING (aquaculture), BEE KEEPING (apiculture — honey, beeswax). Proper shelter, balanced feed, disease prevention, and breeding are essential.',explanation:'Just like crops need care, farm animals need proper food, clean shelter, vaccinations, and good breeding to produce maximum quality products.',teacherTip:'Apiculture = bees (Api = Latin for bee). Aquaculture = fish. Poultry = birds.',examTip:'Know the specific terms: apiculture, aquaculture, poultry, dairy farming.'},
// TRUE/FALSE
{id:"b9tf1",topicId:"bio-ch9",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Fertilizers are always better than manure for crops.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:"False. While fertilizers provide quick nutrients, excessive use can damage soil structure, pollute water bodies, and reduce soil fertility long-term. Manure improves soil texture and adds humus.",teacherTip:'Fertilizers = fast but risky. Manure = slow but sustainable.',examTip:'Mention disadvantages of excessive fertilizer use: soil degradation, water pollution.'},
{id:"b9tf2",topicId:"bio-ch9",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Apiculture refers to the rearing of fish.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:"False. Apiculture is BEE-KEEPING (for honey and beeswax). Fish rearing is called AQUACULTURE or pisciculture.",teacherTip:'Api = bee (Latin). Aqua = water. Pisci = fish. Learn the Latin roots!',examTip:'Know: Apiculture=bees, Aquaculture=fish, Sericulture=silkworms, Poultry=birds.'},
// MCQ
{id:"b9mcq1",topicId:"bio-ch9",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"NPK in fertilizers stands for:",options:["Nitrogen, Phosphorus, Potassium","Nitrogen, Protein, Keratin","Niacin, Phosphorus, Kalium","None of the above"],correctOption:0,answer:"NPK stands for Nitrogen (N), Phosphorus (P), and Potassium (K — from Kalium). These are the three primary nutrients needed for plant growth.",teacherTip:'N = leaf growth. P = root/flower growth. K = overall plant health.',examTip:'Remember K = Potassium (from Latin "Kalium"), not just "K."'},
// SHORT ANSWER
{id:"b9sa1",topicId:"bio-ch9",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Differentiate between manure and fertilizers.",answer:'MANURE:\n• Natural/organic material (decomposed plant and animal waste)\n• Provides nutrients slowly over time\n• Improves soil structure and water-holding capacity\n• Adds humus to soil\n• Eco-friendly, no pollution\n• Example: Compost, farmyard manure, vermicompost\n\nFERTILIZERS:\n• Chemical/synthetic substances manufactured in factories\n• Provides nutrients quickly in specific amounts\n• Does NOT improve soil structure\n• No humus added\n• Overuse causes soil and water pollution\n• Example: Urea, NPK, superphosphate',teacherTip:'Manure = slow food for soil. Fertilizer = fast food for soil (convenient but not always healthy).',examTip:'Compare at least 5 features in a table format for maximum marks.'},
];
